Priebke, a mass murderer who never repented his crimes, died on Friday aged 100 as he was serving a life sentence in Rome for his part in the 1944 massacre of the Ardeatine Caves.

Nazi officers rounded up and shot more than 300 Italian men and boys in a reprisal attack for the killing of German soldiers by resistance fighters. It is considered the worst atrocity of World War II on Italian soil.

Despite being explicitly prohibited by the Vatican and the mayor, an ultra-conservative Christian sect had offered to conduct the ceremony, although not a burial.

The Society of Saint Pius X, which has split from the Vatican gained notoriety in 2009 when a British member, Richard Williamson, denied the Holocaust had taken place.

